{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17502028","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17502028"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:38:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1818"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1818"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.13,0.02,0.44,0.3]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86187"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1818","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1818"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1818"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70456"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"17"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"928"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1339"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1384"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14822"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29559"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86187","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/86187"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with abdominal pain and is admitted to hospital. He undergoes a total gastrectomy for gastric adenocarcinoma and is making good progress. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOvernight, on his fifth day of hospitalisation after the procedure, he develops severe chest pain. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. An ECG shows changes consistent with an acute anterior myocardial infarction. The intern contacts the duty medical team, who attend to the patient and ensure that his condition is stabilised. The patient understands what has caused his chest pain. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe surgical registrar is informed of the events. The patient\u0027s wife is listed as his next of kin in the medical record and has been making daily visits, however is not currently in attendance. The patient does not take any regular medications and has no other significant medical history.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step for the intern?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Document the event in the medical record only","Inform the duty surgical consultant","Inform the patient\u0027s General Practitioner","Inform the patient\u0027s wife, with his consent","Check for an Advance Care Directive"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn this scenario the most appropriate next step for the intern is to \u003Cstrong\u003Einform the patient\u0027s wife, with his consent\u003C/strong\u003E. This action ensures that the family is kept up to date with significant changes in the patient\u0027s condition and aligns with the principles of patient-centered care, maintaining open communication with the family. This is crucial in managing unexpected events during a hospital stay and helps maintain trust between the healthcare team and the patient\u0027s family, allowing the family to provide support during this unexpected complication. However, it\u0027s crucial to obtain the patient\u0027s consent before sharing this information, respecting his autonomy and right to privacy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt should be noted however that there are several actions required of the intern in this situation. This includes \u003Cstrong\u003Edetermining if the patient has an Advance Care Directive (ACD)\u003C/strong\u003E, however given the patient is showing no signs of incapacity at the current moment this does not need to occur immediately. The patient is stable and able to communicate his wishes, so immediate reference to an ACD is not necessary.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdditionally, while \u003Cstrong\u003Einforming the duty surgical consultant\u003C/strong\u003E may be necessary, it is not the most pressing action at this moment. The surgical registrar has already been informed, and the patient has been stabilised by the medical team.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocumenting the event in the medical record only\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient. While documentation is important, it does not address the need to communicate with the patient\u0027s family about this significant change in his condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInforming the patient\u0027s General Practitioner\u003C/strong\u003E is not the immediate priority. While the GP should be updated at some point, the patient\u0027s family should be informed first about this acute event.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Keeping family members informed of changes in a patient\u0027s condition should always be a priority in management, with the patient\u0027s consent.","Communication with family members is an essential part of patient-centered care and helps maintain trust in the healthcare team."],"references":["SA Health. Advance Care Directives. Government of South Australia; 2020 [cited 2025 Feb 19]. Available from: https://www.sahealth.sa.gov.au/wps/wcm/connect/public+content/sa+health+internet/conditions/end+of+life+care/advance+care+directives/advance+care+directives","Shah P, Thornton I, Turrin D, Hipskind JE. Informed Consent. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2022 Jun 11 [cited 2025 Feb 19]. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK430827/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70456"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1818"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"70456","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/70456"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-19T19:08:42+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-19T19:09:19+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1818"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"86187"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"17","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/17"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude07","name":"Bioethics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount"